azine)|BBC History Magazine]]|volume=10|issue=2|pages=26\u201333|date=February 2009}}\n* Furneaux, R.. ''The Zulu War: Isandhlwana & Rorke's Drift'' W&N (Great Battles of History Series), 1963.\n* {{London Gazette|issue=24695|page=2199|date=14 March 1879}}\n* Greaves, Adrian. ''Isandlwana'', Cassell & Co, 2001, {{ISBN|0-304-35700-6}}.\n* Greaves, Adrian. ''Rorke's Drift'', Cassell & Co., 2003 {{ISBN|0-304-36641-2}}.\n* Jackson, F.W.D. ''Hill of the Sphinx'' London, 2002.\n* Jackson, F.W.D. and Whybra, Julian ''Isandhlwana and the Durnford Papers'', (Journal of the Victorian Military Society, March 1990, Issue 60).\n* Knight, Ian ''Brave Men's Blood'', London, 1990. {{ISBN|1-84415-212-X}}.\n* Knight, Ian ''Zulu'', (London, 1992)\n* Knight, Ian ''Zulu Rising'', London, 2010. {{ISBN|0-330-44593-6}}.\n* Whybra, Julian. ''England's Sons'', Billericay, (7th ed.), 2010.\n* Yorke, Edmund. ''Isandlwana 1879''. 2016.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Battle of Isandlwana}}\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/history/british/victorians/zulu_08.shtml Zulu: The True Story By Dr. Saul David]\n* [http://1stzulusafaris.co.za/battlefields.html Isandlwana battlefields]\n* [http://www.richthofen.com/smith-dorrien/dorrien01a.htm Personal account of the battle by Horace Smith-Dorrien]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070928150914/http://www.zulunet.co.za/izl/isandlwana.htm Zulunet description of the battle]\n* [https://www.pbs.org/wnet/secrets/case_zulu/ Secrets of the Dead \u2013 Day of the Zulu]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090703235538/http://www.travellersimpressions.com/process/articlepage.php?storycode=rg0003 Travellers Impressions]\n* [http://www.britishbattles.com/zulu-war/isandlwana.htm The Battle of Isandlwana]\n* The Battle of Isandlwana 22 January 1879, Ian Knight video [https://web.archive.org/web/20130320041504/http://www.ianknightzulu.com/battle-isandlwana-22-january-1879]\n* Forgotten Heroes Zulu & Basuto Wars, Roy Dutton,/ [https://www.roydutton.co.uk/my-books/forgotten-heroes-zulu-basuto-wars/\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Isandlwana, Battle Of}}\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1879]]\n[[Category:1879 in the Zulu Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Battles of the Anglo-Zulu War]]\n[[Category:KwaZulu-Natal]]\n[[Category:Military history of South Africa]]\n[[Category:Battles involving the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:History of KwaZulu-Natal]]\n[[Category:January 1879 events]]\n", "name_user": "JuliusPepperwoodExCopExMarine", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eOrder of battle:minor fix and revision", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_Isandlwana"}
{"title_page": "Disappearance of Garrett Bardsley", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Garrett Bardsley\n| image              = \n| caption            =\n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|df=y|1992|7|24}}\n| birth_place        = \n| disappeared_date   = {{Disappeared date and age|2004|8|20|1992|7|24|df=yes}}\n| disappeared_status = {{Missing for|2004|8|20}}\n| nationality        = [[United States|American]]\n| occupation         = \n| height             = \n| mother             = \n| father             = Kevin Bardsley\n| relatives          = \n}}\n'''Garrett Bardsley''' (born 24 July 1992) disappeared from the Cuberant Lake in the Uinta Mountains of Utah on 20 August 2004 when he was 12 years old. On that day, he was fishing with his father when his feet got wet so he started to walk back to the campsite to change his shoes. He never arrived at the campsite. He was last seen wearing red sweatpants, a T-shirt, a black hooded sweatshirt, and Converse tennis shoes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.missingkids.org/poster/ncmc/995300/1.html|title=Have you seen this child? Garrett Bardsley|website=missingkids.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n== The Garrett Bardsley Foundation ==\nThe Garrett Bardsley Foundation was set up by Bardsley's father.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.findgarrett.org/|title=Welcome to FindGarrett.org|website=www.findgarrett.org|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{uncategorized|date=April 2020}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Garrett Bardsley\n| image              = \n| caption            =\n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|df=y|1992|7|24}}\n| birth_place        = \n| disappeared_date   = {{Disappeared date and age|2004|8|20|1992|7|24|df=yes}}\n| disappeared_status = {{Missing for|2004|8|20}}\n| nationality        = [[United States|American]]\n| occupation         = \n| height             = \n| mother             = \n| father             = Kevin Bardsley\n| relatives          = \n}}\n'''Garrett Bardsley''' (born 24 July 1992) disappeared from the Cuberant Lake in the Uinta Mountains of Utah on 20 August 2004 when he was 12 years old. On that day, he was fishing with his father when his feet got wet so he started to walk back to the campsite to change his shoes. He never arrived at the campsite. He was last seen wearing red sweatpants, a T-shirt, a black hooded sweatshirt, and Converse tennis shoes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.missingkids.org/poster/ncmc/995300/1.html|title=Have you seen this child? Garrett Bardsley|website=missingkids.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n== The Garrett Bardsley Foundation ==\nThe Garrett Bardsley Foundation was set up by Bardsley's father.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.findgarrett.org/|title=Welcome to FindGarrett.org|website=www.findgarrett.org|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{uncategorised|date=April 2020}}\n", "name_user": "CAPTAIN RAJU", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Disappearance_of_Garrett_Bardsley"}
{"title_page": "Nambashi", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=May 2018}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Nambashi\n| native_name             = \n| native_name_lang        = Nambashi tui\n| other_name              = Nambashi Khullen, Nambashi Khunou, Nambashi Horton, Nambashi Kachumram, Nambashi Valley\n| nickname                = \n| settlement_type         = Village\n| image_skyline           = \n| image_alt               = \n| image_caption           = \n| pushpin_map             = India Manipur#India\n| pushpin_label_position  = left\n| pushpin_map_alt         = \n| pushpin_map_caption     = Location in Manipur, India\n| coordinates             = {{coord|24|35|48|N|94|20|57|E|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = {{flag|India}}\n| subdivision_type1       = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Manipur]]\n| subdivision_type2       = [[List of districts of India|District]]\n| subdivision_name2       = [[Kamjong]]\n| established_title       = <!-- Established -->\n| established_date        = \n| founder                 = \n| named_for               = \n| government_type         = [[Panchayati raj (India)]]\n| governing_body          = [[Gram panchayat]] \n| unit_pref               = Metric\n| area_footnotes          = \n| area_rank               = \n| area_total_km2          = \n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_m             = \n| population_total        = 2300\n| population_as_of        = \n| population_rank         = \n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_demonym      = \n| population_footnotes    = \n| demographics_type1      = Languages\n| demographics1_title1    = Official\n| demographics1_info1     = [[Nambashi Dialect]], [[Tangkhul]], [[Manipuri language|Manipuri]] and [[English language|English]]\n| timezone1               = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1             = +5:30\n| postal_code_type        = [[Postal Index Number|PIN]]\n| postal_code             = 795142\n| registration_plate      = MN \n| blank1_name_sec1        = Nearest city\n| blank1_info_sec1        = [[Imphal]], [[Ukhrul]]\n| blank2_name_sec1        = Literacy\n| blank2_info_sec1        = 95.42%\n| blank3_name_sec1        = [[Lok Sabha]] constituency\n| blank3_info_sec1        = Outer Manipur\n| blank4_name_sec1        = [[Vidhan Sabha]] constituency\n| blank4_info_sec1        = [[Phungyar]]\n| website                 = {{URL|manipur.gov.in}} \n| footnotes               = \n}}\n'''Nambashi''' is a common reference to five villages in [[Kamjong District]], [[Manipur]] state, [[India]]. Nambashi comprises of Nambashi Khullen, Nambashi Khunou, Nambashi Horton, Nambashi Kachumram and Nambashi Valley. The villages fall under [[Kasom]] sub division. The village is partially connected by Ukhrul-Phungyar state highway and Shangshak-Yairipok district road. Nambashi is flanked by [[Tarong, Manipur|Tarong]] in the west, [[Kashung]] in the south, [[Punge]] and [[Sorde, Manipur|Sorde]] in the east and [[Kasom]] in the north. Locally, the inhabitants speak Nambashi dialect that belongs to the Tibeto-Burman language family. \n__TOC__\n\n==Total population== \nAccording to 2011 census,<ref>{{cite web |url=http:www.census2011.co.in/data/subdistrict/1891-ukhrul-south-ukhrul-manipur.html|title=Nambashi|publisher=Census 2011|accessdate=2019-11-11 }}</ref>the four villages altogether comprise of  has 247 households with the total of 1308.\n\n==People and occupation==\nThe village is home to people of [[Tangkhul Naga]] tribe. Majority of the inhabitants are Christians. Agriculture is the primary occupation of the inhabitants. The village is known in the district for its reserve natural environment, flora and fauna. In December 2018, a rural market was inaugurated at Nambashi Khullen under the Mission for Integrated Development of Horticulture (MIDH) to boost cultivation and sale of local agricultural products. [[Leishiyo Keishing]], hails from Nambashi Horton village. <ref>{{cite web |url=http://e-pao.net/GP.asp?src=1..271218.dec18|title=Local Market at Nambashi|publisher=e-pao|accessdate=2019-11-11 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Ukhrul district]]\n[[Category:Villages in Kamjong district]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=May 2018}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Nambashi\n| native_name             = \n| native_name_lang        = Nambashi tui\n| other_name              = Nambashi Khullen, Nambashi Khunou, Nambashi Horton, Nambashi Kachumram, Nambashi Valley\n| nickname                = \n| settlement_type         = Village\n| image_skyline           = \n| image_alt               = \n| image_caption           = \n| pushpin_map             = India Manipur#India\n| pushpin_label_position  = left\n| pushpin_map_alt         = \n| pushpin_map_caption     = Location in Manipur, India\n| coordinates             = {{coord|24|35|48|N|94|20|57|E|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = {{flag|India}}\n| subdivision_type1       = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Manipur]]\n| subdivision_type2       = [[List of districts of India|District]]\n| subdivision_name2       = [[Kamjong]]\n| established_title       = <!-- Established -->\n| established_date        = \n| founder                 = \n| named_for               = \n| government_type         = [[Panchayati raj (India)]]\n| governing_body          = [[Gram panchayat]] \n| unit_pref               = Metric\n| area_footnotes          = \n| area_rank               = \n| area_total_km2          = \n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_m             = \n| population_total        = 2300\n| population_as_of        = \n| population_rank         = \n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_demonym      = \n| population_footnotes    = \n| demographics_type1      = Languages\n| demographics1_title1    = Official\n| demographics1_info1     = [[Nambashi Dialect]], [[Tangkhul]], [[Manipuri]] and [[English language|English]]\n| timezone1               = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1             = +5:30\n| postal_code_type        = [[Postal Index Number|PIN]]\n| postal_code             = 795142\n| registration_plate      = MN \n| blank1_name_sec1        = Nearest city\n| blank1_info_sec1        = [[Imphal]], [[Ukhrul]]\n| blank2_name_sec1        = Literacy\n| blank2_info_sec1        = 95.42%\n| blank3_name_sec1        = [[Lok Sabha]] constituency\n| blank3_info_sec1        = Outer Manipur\n| blank4_name_sec1        = [[Vidhan Sabha]] constituency\n| blank4_info_sec1        = [[Phungyar]]\n| website                 = {{URL|manipur.gov.in}} \n| footnotes               = \n}}\n'''Nambashi''' is a common reference to five villages in [[Kamjong District]], [[Manipur]] state, [[India]]. Nambashi comprises of Nambashi Khullen, Nambashi Khunou, Nambashi Horton, Nambashi Kachumram and Nambashi Valley. The villages fall under [[Kasom]] sub division. The village is partially connected by Ukhrul-Phungyar state highway and Shangshak-Yairipok district road. Nambashi is flanked by [[Tarong, Manipur|Tarong]] in the west, [[Kashung]] in the south, [[Punge]] and [[Sorde, Manipur|Sorde]] in the east and [[Kasom]] in the north. Locally, the inhabitants speak Nambashi dialect that belongs to the Tibeto-Burman language family. \n__TOC__\n\n==Total population== \nAccording to 2011 census,<ref>{{cite web |url=http:www.census2011.co.in/data/subdistrict/1891-ukhrul-south-ukhrul-manipur.html|title=Nambashi|publisher=Census 2011|accessdate=2019-11-11 }}</ref>the four villages altogether comprise of  has 247 households with the total of 1308.\n\n==People and occupation==\nThe village is home to people of [[Tangkhul Naga]] tribe. Majority of the inhabitants are Christians. Agriculture is the primary occupation of the inhabitants. The village is known in the district for its reserve natural environment, flora and fauna. In December 2018, a rural market was inaugurated at Nambashi Khullen under the Mission for Integrated Development of Horticulture (MIDH) to boost cultivation and sale of local agricultural products. [[Leishiyo Keishing]], hails from Nambashi Horton village. <ref>{{cite web |url=http://e-pao.net/GP.asp?src=1..271218.dec18|title=Local Market at Nambashi|publisher=e-pao|accessdate=2019-11-11 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Ukhrul district]]\n[[Category:Villages in Kamjong district]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toManipuri(link changed toManipuri language) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nambashi"}
{"title_page": "Kyoko Hamaguchi", "text_new": "{{short description|Japanese freestyle wrestler}}\n{{MedalTableTop\n|image=\u6d45\u8349 \u6d45\u8349\u5bfa\u7bc0\u5206\u4f1a 2015 \u6d5c\u53e3\u4eac\u5b50 \u30a2\u30cb\u30de\u30eb\u6d5c\u53e3 \u6d45\u8349\u89b3\u97f3\u6587\u5316\u82b8\u80fd\u4eba\u7bc0\u5206\u4f1a 2015.jpg\n|image_size=200px\n}}\n{{MedalSport | Women's [[wrestling]]}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{JPN}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Wrestling at the Summer Olympics|Summer Olympics]]}}\n{{MedalBronze  | [[2004 Summer Olympics|2004 Athens]] | [[Wrestling at the 2004 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's freestyle 72 kg|72 kg]]}}\n{{MedalBronze  | [[2008 Summer Olympics|2008 Beijing]] | [[Wrestling at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's freestyle 72 kg|72 kg]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FILA Wrestling World Championships|World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1997 FILA Wrestling World Championships|1997 Clermond-Ferrand]]|75 kg}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1998 FILA Wrestling World Championships|1998 Poznan]]|75 kg}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1999 FILA Wrestling World Championships|1999 Hildursborg]]|75 kg}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2002 FILA Wrestling World Championships|2002 Chalkida]]|72 kg}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2003 FILA Wrestling World Championships|2003 New York]]|72 kg}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2005 FILA Wrestling World Championships|2005 Budapest]]|72 kg}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2006 FILA Wrestling World Championships|2006 Guangzhou]]|72 kg}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2000 FILA Wrestling World Championships|2000 Sofia]]|75 kg}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2008 FILA Wrestling World Championships|2008 Tokyo]]|72 kg}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2010 FILA Wrestling World Championships|2010 Moscow]]|72 kg}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Asian Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[Wrestling at the 2002 Asian Games|2002 Busan]]|72kg}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[Wrestling at the 2006 Asian Games|2006 Doha]]|72 kg}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[Wrestling at the 2010 Asian Games|2010 Guangzhou]]|72 kg}}\n{{MedalBottom}}\n\n{{Nihongo|'''Kyoko Hamaguchi'''|\u6d5c\u53e3 \u4eac\u5b50|Hamaguchi Ky\u014dko|extra=born January 11, 1978 in [[Taito, Tokyo]]}} is a [[Japan]]ese [[freestyle wrestling|freestyle wrestler]]. She has won five [[FILA Wrestling World Championships]] and two [[Olympic games|Olympic]] Bronze medals in the 72&nbsp;kg weight class.\n\nShe is sponsored by Japan Beverage Inc. and was nominated by the [[Japanese Olympic Committee]]'s Special Athlete Campaign.\n\nHer father is professional wrestler [[Animal Hamaguchi]], who is known for his emotional displays during Kyoko's matches. Although Kyoko has long wanted to follow in her father's footsteps and enter the professional game, the lack of a stable women's circuit since the collapse of [[All Japan Women's Pro-Wrestling]] has kept her from doing so.\n\n== Profile ==\nShe [[swimming (sport)|swam]] while in junior high school. At the age of fourteen, she decided that she wanted to be a female professional wrestler and trained in the Animal Hamaguchi's Wrestling Dojo.\n\nShe has won the Japan Championship every year from 1996 to 2006, and has won the World Championships five times. In both the [[2004 Athens Olympics]] and the [[2008 Beijing Olympics]], she won a bronze medal in the 72&nbsp;kg class. She was also a flag bearer for the Japanese team in the opening Olympic ceremonies in 2004.\n\n== Results ==\n*1996 - win - Japan Championship (70&nbsp;kg)\n*1997 - win - Japan Championship (70&nbsp;kg)\n*1997 - win - World Championship (75&nbsp;kg)\n*1998 - win - Japan Championship (75&nbsp;kg)\n*1998 - win - World Championship (75&nbsp;kg)\n*1998 - FILA's female wrestler of the year\n*1999 - win - Japan Championship (75&nbsp;kg)\n*1999 - win - World Championship (75&nbsp;kg)\n*2000 - win - Japan Championship (75&nbsp;kg)\n*2001 - win - Japan Championship (75&nbsp;kg)\n*2001 - win - East Asia Competition\n*2002 - win - Japan Championship (72&nbsp;kg)\n*2002 - win - World Championship (72&nbsp;kg)\n*2002 - win - [[2002 Asian Games|Asian Games at Busan]] (72&nbsp;kg)\n*2003 - win - Japan Championship (72&nbsp;kg)\n*2003 - win - World Championship (72&nbsp;kg)\n*2004 - 2nd - Testing Competition for Athens Olympics (72&nbsp;kg)\n*2004 - 3rd - [[2004 Summer Olympics|Athens Olympics]] (72&nbsp;kg)\n*2004 - win - Japan Championship (72&nbsp;kg)\n*2005 - 2nd - World Championship (72&nbsp;kg)\n*2005 - win - Japan Championship (72&nbsp;kg) (winning for 10 years), MVP ({{Nihongo|\u5929\u7687\u676f|Ten'noh-hai}})\n*2006 - win - Japan Queen's Cup (72&nbsp;kg)\n*2006 - 2nd - World Cup (72&nbsp;kg)\n*2006 - 2nd - [[2006 Asian Games|Asian Games]] (72&nbsp;kg)\n*2007 - 2nd - Asia Championship (72&nbsp;kg)\n*2008 - 2nd - Asia Championship (72&nbsp;kg)\n*2008 - 3rd - [[2008 Summer Olympics|Beijing Olympics]] (72&nbsp;kg)\n\n== Awards ==\n*'''''[[Tokyo Sports]]'''''\n**[[Tokyo Sports Puroresu Awards#Wrestling Special Award|Wrestling Special Award]] (1998, 1999, 2002-2006)<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.tokyo-sports.co.jp/wrestling/wrestling_past3/ | title = \u6771\u4eac\u30b9\u30dd\u30fc\u30c4\u3000\u30d7\u30ed\u30ec\u30b9\u5927\u8cde\uff1a\u9078\u8003\u7d4c\u904e\uff081990\uff5e1999\uff09 | accessdate=December 16, 2017 | work=[[Tokyo Sports]] | language=Japanese}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.tokyo-sports.co.jp/wrestling/wrestling_past4/ | title = \u6771\u4eac\u30b9\u30dd\u30fc\u30c4\u3000\u30d7\u30ed\u30ec\u30b9\u5927\u8cde\uff1a\u9078\u8003\u7d4c\u904e\uff082000\uff5e2009\uff09 | accessdate=December 16, 2017 | work=[[Tokyo Sports]] | language=Japanese}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.fila-wrestling.com/moscow10/index.php?option=com_competition&act=ficheLutteur&style=FW&choix_poids=2620&Itemid=157&choix_pays=*&id_inscrit=49754&act2=lutteur&lang=en bio on fila-wrestling.com]{{Dead link|date=February 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n* {{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ha/kyoko-hamaguchi-1.html |title=Kyoko Hamaguchi}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-sports|oly}}\n{{succession box\n